    name:"HCG (Human Chorionic Gonadotropin)",category:"Hormonal",emoji:"🧪",
    summary:"LH mimic. Directly stimulates testes. Essential for TRT users wanting to preserve fertility and testicular size.",
    description:`HCG is a glycoprotein hormone naturally produced during pregnancy. In men's health, it is used to maintain or restore testicular function by mimicking LH (Luteinizing Hormone) — the signal that tells testes to produce testosterone.

HCG's beta subunit is structurally similar to LH and binds LH receptors on testicular Leydig cells, directly stimulating testosterone production. This bypasses the entire hypothalamus-pituitary loop, going straight to the testes.

During TRT (testosterone replacement therapy): exogenous testosterone creates negative feedback shutting down the HPG axis. The testes stop producing testosterone naturally, leading to testicular atrophy and infertility. HCG prevents this by directly stimulating the testes regardless of hypothalamic-pituitary suppression.

For PCT (post-cycle therapy): after anabolic steroid cycles suppressing the HPG axis, HCG is typically the first step — restarting the testes directly — followed by SERMs (enclomiphene/tamoxifen) to restart the hypothalamus and pituitary.

The standard PCT sequence: HCG (2–3 weeks) to wake the testes, then enclomiphene (4–6 weeks) to restore the whole HPG cascade.`,
